# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: windows-internals
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] The architecture of Windows NT, a line of operating systems produced and sold by Microsoft, is a layered design that consists of two main components, user mode and kernel mode.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] It is a preemptive, reentrant multitasking operating system, which has been designed to work with uniprocessor and symmetrical multiprocessor (SMP)-based computers.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] To process input/output (I/O) requests, it uses packet-driven I/O, which utilizes I/O request packets (IRPs) and asynchronous I/O.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] Starting with Windows XP, Microsoft began making 64-bit versions of Windows available; before this, there were only 32-bit versions of these operating systems.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] Programs and subsystems in user mode are limited in terms of what system resources they have access to, while the kernel mode has unrestricted access to the system memory and external devices.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] Kernel mode in Windows NT has full access to the hardware and system resources of the computer.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] The Windows NT kernel is a hybrid kernel; the architecture comprises a simple kernel, hardware abstraction layer (HAL), drivers, and a range of services (collectively named Executive), which all exist in kernel mode.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] User mode in Windows NT is made of subsystems capable of passing I/O requests to the appropriate kernel mode device drivers by using the I/O manager.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] The user mode layer of Windows NT is made up of the "Environment subsystems", which run applications written for many different types of operating systems, and the "Integral subsystem", which operates system-specific functions on behalf of environment subsystems.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] The kernel mode stops user mode services and applications from accessing critical areas of the operating system that they should not have access to.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] The Executive interfaces, with all the user mode subsystems, deal with I/O, object management, security and process management.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] The kernel sits between the hardware abstraction layer and the Executive to provide *multiprocessor synchronization*, thread and interrupt scheduling and dispatching, and trap handling and exception dispatching.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] The kernel is also responsible for initializing device drivers at bootup.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] Kernel mode drivers exist in three levels: highest level drivers, intermediate drivers and low-level drivers.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] Windows Driver Model (WDM) exists in the intermediate layer and was mainly designed to be binary and source compatible between Windows 98 and Windows 2000.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] The lowest level drivers are either legacy Windows NT device drivers that control a device directly or can be a plug and play (PnP) hardware bus.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] User mode is made up of various system-defined processes and DLLs.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] The interface between user mode applications and operating system kernel functions is called an "environment subsystem." Windows NT can have more than one of these, each implementing a different API set.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] This mechanism was designed to support applications written for many different types of operating systems.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] None of the environment subsystems can directly access hardware; access to hardware functions is done by calling into kernel mode routines.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] There are three main environment subsystems: the Win32 subsystem, an OS/2 subsystem and a POSIX subsystem.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] The Win32 environment subsystem can run 32-bit Windows applications.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] It contains the console as well as text window support, shutdown and hard-error handling for all other environment subsystems.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] It also supports Virtual DOS Machines (VDMs), which allow MS-DOS and 16-bit Windows (Win16) applications to run on Windows NT.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] There is a specific MS-DOS VDM that runs in its own address space and which emulates an Intel 80486 running MS-DOS 5.0.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] Win16 programs, however, run in a Win16 VDM.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] Each program, by default, runs in the same process, thus using the same address space, and the Win16 VDM gives each program its own thread on which to run.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] However, Windows NT does allow users to run a Win16 program in a separate Win16 VDM, which allows the program to be preemptively multitasked, as Windows NT will pre-empt the whole VDM process, which only contains one running application.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] The Win32 environment subsystem process (`csrss.exe`) also includes the window management functionality, sometimes called a "window manager".
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] It handles input events (such as from the keyboard and mouse), then passes messages to the applications that need to receive this input.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] Each application is responsible for drawing or refreshing its own windows and menus, in response to these messages.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] The OS/2 environment subsystem supports 16-bit character-based OS/2 applications and emulates OS/2 1.x, but not 32-bit or graphical OS/2 applications as used with OS/2 2.x or later, on x86 machines only.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] To run graphical OS/2 1.x programs, the Windows NT Add-On Subsystem for Presentation Manager must be installed.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] The last version of Windows NT to have an OS/2 subsystem was Windows 2000; it has been discontinued as of Windows XP.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] The POSIX environment subsystem supports applications that are strictly written to either the POSIX.1 standard or the related ISO/IEC standards.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] This subsystem has been replaced by Interix, which is a part of Windows Services for UNIX.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] This was in turn replaced by the Windows Subsystem for Linux.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] The security subsystem "manages operating system-specific functions on behalf of the environment system and consists of a security system process".
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] The workstation service implements the network redirector, which is the client side of Windows file and print sharing; it implements local requests to remote files and printers by "redirecting" them to the appropriate servers on the network.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] Conversely, the server service allows other computers on the network to access file shares and shared printers offered by the local system.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] Windows NT kernel mode has full access to the hardware and system resources of the computer and runs code in a protected memory area.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] It controls access to scheduling, thread prioritization, memory management and the interaction with hardware.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] The kernel mode stops user mode services and applications from accessing critical areas of the operating system that they should not have access to; user mode processes must ask the kernel mode to perform such operations on their behalf.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] While the x86 architecture supports four different privilege levels (numbered 0 to 3), only the two extreme privilege levels are used.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] Usermode programs are run with CPL 3, and the kernel runs with CPL 0.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] These two levels are often referred to as "ring 3" and "ring 0", respectively.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] Such a design decision had been done to achieve code portability to RISC platforms that only support two privilege levels, though this breaks compatibility with OS/2 applications that contain I/O privilege segments that attempt to directly access hardware.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] Code running in kernel mode includes: the executive, which is itself made up of many modules that do specific tasks; the kernel, which provides low-level services used by the Executive; the Hardware Abstraction Layer (HAL); and *kernel drivers*.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] The Windows Executive services make up the low-level kernel-mode portion, and are contained in the file `ntoskrnl.exe`.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] It deals with I/O, object management, security and process management.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] These are divided into several *subsystems*, among which are *Cache Manager*, *Configuration Manager*, *I/O Manager*, *Local Procedure Call (LPC)*, *Memory Manager*, *Object Manager*, *Process Structure* and *Security Reference Monitor (SRM)*.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] Grouped together, the components can be called *Executive services* (internal name *Ex*).
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] *System Services* (internal name *Nt*), i.e., system calls, are implemented at this level, too, except very few that call directly into the kernel layer for better performance.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] The term "service" in this context generally refers to a callable routine, or set of callable routines.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] This is distinct from the concept of a "service process", which is a user mode component somewhat analogous to a daemon in Unix-like operating systems.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] ) is an executive subsystem that all other executive subsystems, especially system calls, must pass through to gain access to Windows NT resources—essentially making it a resource management infrastructure service.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] The object manager is used to reduce the duplication of object resource management functionality in other executive subsystems, which could potentially lead to bugs and make development of Windows NT harder.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] To the object manager, each resource is an object, whether that resource is a physical resource (such as a file system or peripheral) or a logical resource (such as a file).
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] that the object manager must know about.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] causes the allocation of an empty object and the reservation of any resources required by the object manager, such as an (optional) name in the namespace.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] If creation was successful, the subsystem responsible for the creation fills in the empty object.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] From then on, the lifetime of the object is handled by the object manager, and it's up to the subsystem to keep the object in a working condition until being signaled by the object manager to dispose of it.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] Handles are identifiers that represent a reference to a kernel resource through an opaque value.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] Similarly, opening an object through its name is subject to security checks, but acting through an existing, open handle is only limited to the level of access requested when the object was opened or created.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] Object types define the object procedures and any data specific to the object.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] Most subsystems, though, with a notable exception in the I/O Manager, rely on the default implementation for all object type procedures.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] Each instance of an object that is created stores its name, parameters that are passed to the object creation function, security attributes and a pointer to its object type.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] The object also contains an object close procedure and a reference count to tell the object manager how many other objects in the system reference that object and thereby determines whether the object can be destroyed when a close request is sent to it.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] Closely coordinates with the Memory Manager, I/O Manager and I/O drivers to provide a common cache for regular file I/O.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] , since cache blocks are a special case of memory-mapped views and cache misses a special case of page faults.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] Allows devices to communicate with user-mode subsystems.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] I/O requests and translates them into device specific calls, and can incorporate low-level device drivers that directly manipulate hardware to either read input or write output.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] It also includes a cache manager to improve disk performance by caching read requests and write to the disk in the background.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] Provides inter-process communication ports with connection semantics.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] of memory in and out of physical memory to secondary storage, and implements a general-purpose allocator of physical memory.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] It also implements a parser of PE executables that lets an executable be mapped or unmapped in a single, atomic step.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] , a range of kernel-mode memory that is subject to context switching just like user-mode memory.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] This lets multiple instances of the kernel-mode Win32 subsystem and GDI drivers run side-by-side, despite shortcomings in their initial design.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] Each session space is shared by several processes, collectively referred to as a "session".
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] To ensure a degree of isolation between sessions without introducing a new object type, the association between processes and sessions is handled by the Security Reference Monitor, as an attribute of a security subject (token), and it can only be changed while holding special privileges.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] Starting with Windows Vista, though, sessions finally became a proper aspect of the Windows architecture.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] No longer a memory manager construct that creeps into user mode indirectly through Win32, they were expanded into a pervasive abstraction affecting most Executive subsystems.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] As a matter of fact, regular use of Windows Vista always results in a multi-session environment.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] , a group of processes that can be terminated as a whole, or be placed under shared restrictions (such as the total maximum of allocated memory, or CPU time).
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] and supports device detection and installation at boot time.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] ) gains a new device and needs to have a device driver loaded to support it.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] , which handles the often complex tasks of installing the appropriate drivers, notifying services and applications of the arrival of new devices, and displaying GUI to the user.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] The primary authority for enforcing the security rules of the security integral subsystem.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] (ACLs), which are themselves made up of access control entries (ACEs).
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] —permission (allow, deny, or audit) to that resource.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] is responsible for tasks such as drawing lines and curves, rendering fonts and handling palettes.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] , but this was moved into kernel mode with Windows NT 4.0 to improve graphics performance.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] That is, the kernel performs almost all the tasks of a traditional microkernel; the strict distinction between Executive and Kernel is the most prominent remnant of the original microkernel design, and historical design documentation consistently refers to the kernel component as "the microkernel".
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] The kernel often interfaces with the process manager.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] The level of abstraction is such that the kernel never calls into the process manager, only the other way around (save for a handful of corner cases, still never to the point of a functional dependence).
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] This allows for the possibility of using either direct procedure calls or interprocess communication (IPC) to communicate between modules, and hence for the potential location of modules in different address spaces (for example in either kernel space or server processes).
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] Other design goals shared with Mach included support for diverse architectures, a kernel with abstractions general enough to allow multiple operating system personalities to be implemented on top of it and an object-oriented organisation.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] The primary operating system personality on Windows is the Windows API, which is always present.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] The emulation subsystem which implements the Windows personality is called the Client/Server Runtime Subsystem (`csrss.exe`).
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] On versions of NT prior to 4.0, this subsystem process also contained the window manager, graphics device interface and graphics device drivers.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] For performance reasons, however, in version 4.0 and later, these modules (which are often implemented in user mode even on monolithic systems, especially those designed without internal graphics support) run as a kernel-mode subsystem.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] Applications that run on NT are written to one of the OS personalities (usually the Windows API), and not to the native NT API for which documentation is not publicly available (with the exception of routines used in device driver development).
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] An OS personality is implemented via a set of user-mode DLLs (see Dynamic-link library), which are mapped into application processes' address spaces as required, together with an emulation subsystem server process (as described previously).
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] Applications access system services by calling into the OS personality DLLs mapped into their address spaces, which in turn call into the NT run-time library (`ntdll.dll`), also mapped into the process address space.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] Windows NT uses kernel-mode device drivers to enable it to interact with hardware devices.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] Each of the drivers has well defined system routines and internal routines that it exports to the rest of the operating system.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] All devices are seen by user mode code as a file object in the I/O manager, though to the I/O manager itself the devices are seen as device objects, which it defines as either file, device or driver objects.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] Kernel mode drivers exist in three levels: highest level drivers, intermediate drivers and low level drivers.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] The highest level drivers, such as file system drivers for FAT and NTFS, rely on intermediate drivers.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] Intermediate drivers consist of function drivers—or main driver for a device—that are optionally sandwiched between lower and higher level filter drivers.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] The function driver then relies on a bus driver—or a driver that services a bus controller, adapter, or bridge—which can have an optional bus filter driver that sits between itself and the function driver.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] Intermediate drivers rely on the lowest level drivers to function.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] The Windows Driver Model (WDM) exists in the intermediate layer.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] The lowest level drivers are either legacy Windows NT device drivers that control a device directly or can be a PnP hardware bus.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] These lower level drivers directly control hardware and do not rely on any other drivers.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] The Windows NT hardware abstraction layer (HAL) is a layer between the physical hardware of the computer and the rest of the operating system.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] It was designed to hide differences in hardware and provide a consistent platform on which the kernel is run.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] The HAL includes hardware-specific code that controls I/O interfaces, interrupt controllers and multiple processors.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] However, despite its purpose and designated place within the architecture, the HAL is not a layer that sits entirely below the kernel, the way the kernel sits below the Executive: All known HAL implementations depend in some measure on the kernel, or even the Executive.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] In practice, this means that kernel and HAL variants come in matching sets that are specifically constructed to work together.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] In particular hardware abstraction does *not* involve abstracting the instruction set, which generally falls under the wider concept of portability.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] Abstracting the instruction set, when necessary (such as for handling the several revisions to the x86 instruction set, or emulating a missing math coprocessor), is performed by the kernel, or via hardware virtualization.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] The HAL implements a number of functions that are implemented in different ways by different hardware platforms, which in this context, refers mostly to the chipset.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] Other components in the operating system can then call these functions in the same way on all platforms, without regard for the actual implementation.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] For example, responding to an interrupt is quite different on a machine with an Advanced Programmable Interrupt Controller (APIC) than on one without.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] The HAL provides a single function for this purpose that works with all kinds of interrupts by various chipsets, so that other components need not be concerned with the differences.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] The HAL is loaded into kernel address space and runs in kernel mode, so routines in the HAL cannot be called directly by applications, and no user mode APIs correspond directly to HAL routines.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] Instead, the HAL provides services primarily to the Windows executive and kernel and to kernel mode device drivers.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] Although drivers for most hardware are contained in other files, commonly of file type .sys, a few core drivers are compiled into `hal.dll`.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] Kernel mode device drivers for devices on buses such as PCI and PCI Express directly call routines in the HAL to access I/O ports and registers of their devices.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] The drivers use HAL routines because different platforms may require different implementations of these operations.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] The HAL implements the operations appropriately for each platform, so the same driver executable file can be used on all platforms using the same CPU architecture, and the driver source file can be portable across all architectures.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] On x86 systems prior to Windows 8, there are several different HAL files on the installation media.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] The Windows installation procedure determines which ones are appropriate for the current platform and copies it to the hard drive, renaming it to `hal.dll` if necessary.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] Among the criteria for this selection are: the presence of an ACPI-compatible BIOS, the presence of an APIC, and whether or not multiple processors are present and enabled.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] (The multiple cores of a multi-core CPU, and even the "logical processors" implemented by a hyperthreading CPU, all count as "processors" for this purpose.) On x86-64 and Itanium platforms there is just one possible `hal.dll` for each CPU architecture.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] On Windows 8 and later, the x86 version also only has one HAL.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] The HAL is merged (or statically linked) into `ntoskrnl.exe` starting with version 2004 of Windows 10, and the DLL only serves as a stub for backwards compatibility.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] The boot sequence is initiated by NTLDR in versions before Vista and the Windows Boot Manager in Vista and later.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] The boot loader is responsible for accessing the file system on the boot drive, starting `ntoskrnl.exe`, and loading boot-time device drivers into memory.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] Once all the boot and system drivers have been loaded, the kernel starts the Session Manager Subsystem.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] The session manager starts crucial kernel and user mode services of the Win32 subsystem, such as the Client/Server Runtime Subsystem.
[src:windows-internals/architecture-of-windows-nt] The session also runs process winlogon, allowing the users to login and use their accounts.
[src:windows-internals/native-api] The **Native API** is a lightweight application programming interface (API) used by Windows NT's kernel and user mode applications.
[src:windows-internals/native-api] This API is used in the early stages of Windows NT startup process, when other components and APIs are still unavailable.
[src:windows-internals/native-api] Therefore, a few Windows components, such as the Client/Server Runtime Subsystem (CSRSS), are implemented using the Native API.
[src:windows-internals/native-api] The Native API is also used by subroutines such as those in kernel32.dll that implement the Windows API, the API based on which most of the Windows components are created.
[src:windows-internals/native-api] Most of the Native API calls are implemented in ntoskrnl.exe and are exposed to user mode by **ntdll.dll**.
[src:windows-internals/native-api] The entry point of ntdll.dll is `LdrInitializeThunk`.
[src:windows-internals/native-api] Native API calls are handled by the kernel via the System Service Descriptor Table (SSDT).
[src:windows-internals/native-api] The Native API comprises many functions.
[src:windows-internals/native-api] They include C runtime functions that are needed for a very basic C runtime execution, such as strlen(), sprintf(), memcpy() and floor().
[src:windows-internals/native-api] Other common procedures like malloc(), printf(), scanf() are missing (the first because it does not specify a heap to allocate memory from and the second and third because they use the console, accessed only via KERNEL32.DLL).
[src:windows-internals/native-api] user32.dll and gdi32.dll include several other calls that execute an interrupt into kernel mode.
[src:windows-internals/native-api] These were not part of the original Windows NT design, as can be seen in Windows NT 3.5.
[src:windows-internals/native-api] However, due to performance issues of hardware of that age, it was decided to move the graphics subsystem into kernel mode.
[src:windows-internals/native-api] As such, system call in the range of 0x1000-0x1FFF are satisfied by win32k.sys (instead of ntoskrnl.exe as done for 0-0x0FFF), and are declared in user32.dll and gdi32.dll.
[src:windows-internals/native-api] These functions have the **NtUser** and **NtGdi** prefix (e.g.
[src:windows-internals/native-api] **NtUserLockWorkStation** and **NtGdiEnableEudc**).
[src:windows-internals/object-manager-windows] Object Manager is the centralized resource broker in the Windows NT line of operating systems, which keeps track of the resources allocated to processes.
[src:windows-internals/object-manager-windows] It is resource-agnostic and can manage any type of resource, including device and file handles.
[src:windows-internals/object-manager-windows] All resources are represented as objects, each belonging to a logical namespace for categorization and having a type that represents the type of the resource, which exposes the capabilities and functionalities via properties.
[src:windows-internals/object-manager-windows] An object is kept available until all processes are done with it; Object Manager maintains the record of which objects are currently in use via reference counting, as well as the ownership information.
[src:windows-internals/object-manager-windows] Any system call that changes the state of resource allocation to processes goes via the Object Manager.
[src:windows-internals/object-manager-windows] Objects can either be *Kernel objects* or *Executive objects*.
[src:windows-internals/object-manager-windows] Kernel objects represent primitive resources such as physical devices, or services such as synchronization, which are required to implement any other type of OS service.
[src:windows-internals/object-manager-windows] Kernel objects are not exposed to user mode code, but are restricted to kernel code.
[src:windows-internals/object-manager-windows] Applications and services running outside the kernel use *Executive objects*, which are exposed by the Windows Executive, along with its components such as the memory manager, scheduler and I/O subsystem.
[src:windows-internals/object-manager-windows] Executive objects encapsulate one or more kernel objects and expose not only the kernel and kernel-mediated resources, but also an expanded set of services that the kernel does.
[src:windows-internals/object-manager-windows] Applications themselves can wrap one or more Executive objects and surface objects that offer certain services.
[src:windows-internals/object-manager-windows] Executive objects are also used by the environment subsystems (such as the Win32 subsystem, the OS/2 subsystem, the POSIX subsystem, etc.) to implement the functionality of the respective environments.
[src:windows-internals/object-manager-windows] Whenever an object is created or opened, a reference to the instance, known as a handle, is created.
[src:windows-internals/object-manager-windows] The Object Manager indexes objects by both their names and handles.
[src:windows-internals/object-manager-windows] Referencing objects by handles is faster since it bypasses name translation.
[src:windows-internals/object-manager-windows] Handles are associated with processes by making an entry in the process's Handle table, which lists the handles it owns, and can be transferred between processes.
[src:windows-internals/object-manager-windows] A process must own a handle to an object to use it, and can own up to 16,000,000 handles at one time.
[src:windows-internals/object-manager-windows] During creation, a process gains handles to a default set of objects.
[src:windows-internals/object-manager-windows] There are different types of handles, such as file handles, event handles, and process handles, which identify the type of target objects but do not distinguish the operations that can be performed through them.
[src:windows-internals/object-manager-windows] This consistency ensures uniform handling of various object types programmatically.
[src:windows-internals/object-manager-windows] Handle creation and resolution of objects from handles are exclusively managed by the Object Manager, ensuring that no resource usage goes unnoticed.
[src:windows-internals/object-manager-windows] Each object managed by the Object Manager has a header and a body; the header contains state information used by Object Manager, whereas the body contains the object-specific data and the services it exposes.
[src:windows-internals/object-manager-windows] A `Type` object contains properties unique to the type of the object as well as static methods that implement the services offered by the object.
[src:windows-internals/object-manager-windows] Type objects also have some common attributes, including the type name, whether they are to be allocated in non-paged memory, access rights, and synchronization information.
[src:windows-internals/object-manager-windows] All instances of the same type share the same type object, and the type object is instantiated only once.
[src:windows-internals/object-manager-windows] A new object type can be created by endowing an object with Properties to expose its state and methods to expose the services it offers.
[src:windows-internals/object-manager-windows] `Object name` is used to give a descriptive identity to an object, to aid in object lookup.
[src:windows-internals/object-manager-windows] Object Manager maintains the list of names already assigned to objects being managed, and maps the names to the instances.
[src:windows-internals/object-manager-windows] Since most object accesses occur via handles, it is not always necessary to look up the name to resolve into the object reference.
[src:windows-internals/object-manager-windows] Lookup is only performed when an object is created (to make sure the new object has a unique name), or a process accesses an object by its name explicitly.
[src:windows-internals/object-manager-windows] `Object directories` are used to categorize them according to the types.
[src:windows-internals/object-manager-windows] Each user session is assigned a different namespace.
[src:windows-internals/object-manager-windows] Object Manager paths are available to many Windows API file functions, although Win32 names like \\?\ and \\.\ for the local namespaces suffice for most uses.
[src:windows-internals/object-manager-windows] Using the former in Win32 user-mode functions translates directly to \??, but using \?? is still different as this NT form does not turn off pathname expansion.
[src:windows-internals/object-manager-windows] Tools that serve as explorers in the Object Manager namespaces are available.
[src:windows-internals/object-manager-windows] These include the 32-bit WinObj from Sysinternals and the 64-bit WinObjEx64.
[src:windows-internals/windows-nt] The name "Windows NT" originally denoted the major technological advancements that it had introduced to the Windows product line, including eliminating the 16-bit memory access limitations of earlier Windows releases such as Windows 3.1.
[src:windows-internals/windows-nt] Each Windows release built on this technology is considered to be based on, if not a revision of Windows NT, even though the Windows NT name itself has not been used in any other Windows releases since Windows NT 4.0 in 1996.
[src:windows-internals/windows-nt] Newer versions of Windows NT support 64-bit computing, with a 64-bit kernel and 64-bit memory addressing while retaining compatibility with 32-bit software.
[src:windows-internals/windows-nt] Windows NT is a group or family of products—like Windows is a group or family.
[src:windows-internals/windows-nt] Windows NT is a sub-grouping of Windows.
[src:windows-internals/windows-nt] The first version of Windows NT, 3.1, was produced for workstation and server computers.
[src:windows-internals/windows-nt] It was commercially focused—and intended to complement consumer versions of Windows that were based on MS-DOS (including Windows 1.0 through Windows 3.1x).
[src:windows-internals/windows-nt] In 1996, Windows NT 4.0 was released, including the new shell from Windows 95.
[src:windows-internals/windows-nt] Eventually, Microsoft incorporated the Windows NT technology into the Windows product line for personal computing and deprecated the Windows 9x family.
[src:windows-internals/windows-nt] Starting with Windows 2000, "NT" was removed from the product name yet is still in several low-level places in the system—including for a while as part of the product version.
[src:windows-internals/windows-nt] Versions of Windows NT are installed using Windows Setup, which, starting with Windows Vista, uses the Windows Preinstallation Environment, which is a lightweight version of Windows NT made for deployment of the operating system.
[src:windows-internals/windows-nt] Since Windows Vista, the Windows installation files, as well as the preinstallation environment used to install Windows, are stored in the Windows Imaging Format.
[src:windows-internals/windows-nt] It is possible to use the Deployment Image Servicing and Management (DISM) tool to install Windows from the command line and skip the GUI installer.
[src:windows-internals/windows-nt] It has been suggested that Dave Cutler intended the initialism "WNT" as a play on VMS, incrementing each letter by one.
[src:windows-internals/windows-nt] However, the project was originally intended as a follow-on to OS/2 and was referred to as "NT OS/2" before receiving the Windows brand.
[src:windows-internals/windows-nt] Two of the original NT developers, Mark Lucovsky and Dave W.
[src:windows-internals/windows-nt] Plummer, state that the name was taken from the original target processor—the Intel i860, code-named N10 ("N-Ten").
[src:windows-internals/windows-nt] A 1991 video featuring Bill Gates and Microsoft products specifically says that "Windows NT stands for 'New Technology'".
[src:windows-internals/windows-nt] Seven years later in 1998, during a question-and-answer (Q&A) session, he then revealed that the letters were previously expanded to such but no longer carry any specific meaning.
[src:windows-internals/windows-nt] The letters were dropped from the names of releases from Windows 2000 and later, though Microsoft described that product as being "Built on NT Technology".
[src:windows-internals/windows-nt] "NT" was a trademark of Northern Telecom (later Nortel), which Microsoft was forced to acknowledge on the product packaging.
[src:windows-internals/windows-nt] One of the main purposes of NT is hardware and software portability.
[src:windows-internals/windows-nt] Various versions of NT family operating systems have been released for a variety of processor architectures, initially IA-32, MIPS, and DEC Alpha, with PowerPC, Itanium, x86-64 and ARM supported in later releases.
[src:windows-internals/windows-nt] An initial idea was to have a common code base with a custom Hardware Abstraction Layer (HAL) for each platform.
[src:windows-internals/windows-nt] However, support for MIPS, Alpha, and PowerPC was later dropped in Windows 2000.
[src:windows-internals/windows-nt] Broad software compatibility was initially achieved with support for several API "personalities", including Windows API, POSIX, and OS/2 APIs—the latter two were phased out starting with Windows XP.
[src:windows-internals/windows-nt] Partial MS-DOS and Windows 16-bit compatibility is achieved on IA-32 via an integrated DOS Virtual Machine—although this feature is not available on other architectures.
[src:windows-internals/windows-nt] NT has supported per-object (file, function, and role) access control lists allowing a rich set of security permissions to be applied to systems and services.
[src:windows-internals/windows-nt] NT has also supported Windows network protocols, inheriting the previous OS/2 LAN Manager networking, as well as TCP/IP networking (for which Microsoft used to implement a TCP/IP stack derived at first from a STREAMS-based stack from Spider Systems, then later rewritten in-house).
[src:windows-internals/windows-nt] Windows NT 3.1 was the first version of Windows to use 32-bit flat virtual memory addressing on 32-bit processors.
[src:windows-internals/windows-nt] Its companion product, Windows 3.1, used segmented addressing and switches from 16-bit to 32-bit addressing in pages.
[src:windows-internals/windows-nt] The full preemptive multitasking kernel could interrupt running tasks to schedule other tasks, without relying on user programs to voluntarily give up control of the CPU, as in Windows 3.1 applications (although MS-DOS applications were preemptively multitasked in Windows starting with Windows/386).
[src:windows-internals/windows-nt] Notably, in Windows NT 3.x, several I/O driver subsystems, such as video and printing, were user-mode subsystems.
[src:windows-internals/windows-nt] In Windows NT 4.0, the video, server, and printer spooler subsystems were moved into kernel mode.
[src:windows-internals/windows-nt] Windows NT's first GUI was strongly influenced by (and programmatically compatible with) that from Windows 3.1; Windows NT 4.0's interface was redesigned to match that of the brand-new Windows 95, moving from the Program Manager to the Windows shell design.
[src:windows-internals/windows-nt] NTFS, a journaled, secure file system, is a major feature of NT.
[src:windows-internals/windows-nt] Windows NT also allows for other installable file systems; NT can also be installed on FAT file systems, and versions 3.1, 3.5, and 3.51 could be installed on HPFS file systems.
[src:windows-internals/windows-nt] Windows NT introduced its own driver model, the Windows NT driver model, and is incompatible with older driver frameworks.
[src:windows-internals/windows-nt] With Windows 2000, the Windows NT driver model was enhanced to become the Windows Driver Model, which was first introduced with Windows 98, but was based on the NT driver model.
[src:windows-internals/windows-nt] Windows Vista added native support for the Windows Driver Foundation, which is also available for Windows XP, Windows Server 2003 and to an extent, Windows 2000.
[src:windows-internals/windows-nt] Microsoft decided to create a portable operating system, compatible with OS/2 and POSIX and supporting multiprocessing, in October 1988.
[src:windows-internals/windows-nt] When development started in November 1989, Windows NT was to be known as OS/2 3.0, the third version of the operating system developed jointly by Microsoft and IBM.
[src:windows-internals/windows-nt] To ensure portability, initial development was targeted at the Intel i860XR RISC processor, switching to the MIPS R3000 in late 1989, and then the Intel i386 in 1990.
[src:windows-internals/windows-nt] Microsoft also continued parallel development of the DOS-based and less resource-demanding Windows environment, resulting in the release of Windows 3.0 in May 1990.
[src:windows-internals/windows-nt] Windows 3.0 was eventually so successful that Microsoft decided to change the primary application programming interface for the still unreleased NT OS/2 (as it was then known) from an extended OS/2 API to an extended Windows API.
[src:windows-internals/windows-nt] This decision caused tension between Microsoft and IBM and the collaboration ultimately fell apart.
[src:windows-internals/windows-nt] IBM continued OS/2 development alone while Microsoft continued work on the newly renamed Windows NT.
[src:windows-internals/windows-nt] Though neither operating system would immediately be as popular as Microsoft's MS-DOS or Windows products, Windows NT would eventually be far more successful than OS/2.
[src:windows-internals/windows-nt] The team was joined by selected members of the disbanded OS/2 team, including Moshe Dunie.
[src:windows-internals/windows-nt] Although NT was not an exact clone of Cutler's previous operating systems, DEC engineers almost immediately noticed the internal similarities.
[src:windows-internals/windows-nt] Parts of *VAX/VMS Internals and Data Structures*, published by Digital Press, accurately describe Windows NT internals using VMS terms.
[src:windows-internals/windows-nt] Furthermore, parts of the NT codebase's directory structure and filenames matched that of the MICA codebase.
[src:windows-internals/windows-nt] Instead of a lawsuit, Microsoft agreed to pay DEC $65–100 million, help market VMS, train Digital personnel on Windows NT, and continue Windows NT support for the DEC Alpha.
[src:windows-internals/windows-nt] Windows NT and VMS memory management, processes, and scheduling are very similar.
[src:windows-internals/windows-nt] Windows NT's process management differs by implementing threading, which DEC did not implement until VMS 7.0 in 1995.
[src:windows-internals/windows-nt] Like VMS, Windows NT's kernel mode code distinguishes between the "kernel", whose primary purpose is to implement processor- and architecture-dependent functions, and the "executive".
[src:windows-internals/windows-nt] This was designed as a modified microkernel, as the Windows NT kernel was influenced by the Mach microkernel developed by Richard Rashid at Carnegie Mellon University, but does not meet all of the criteria of a pure microkernel.
[src:windows-internals/windows-nt] Both the kernel and the executive are linked together into the single loaded module ntoskrnl.exe; from outside this module, there is little distinction between the kernel and the executive.
[src:windows-internals/windows-nt] Routines from each are directly accessible, as for example from kernel-mode device drivers.
[src:windows-internals/windows-nt] API sets in the Windows NT family are implemented as subsystems atop the publicly undocumented "native" API; this allowed the late adoption of the Windows API (into the Win32 subsystem).
[src:windows-internals/windows-nt] Windows NT was one of the earliest operating systems to use UCS-2 and UTF-16 internally.
[src:windows-internals/windows-nt] Windows NT uses a layered design architecture that consists of two main components, user mode and kernel mode.
[src:windows-internals/windows-nt] The booting process of Windows NT begins with NTLDR in versions before Vista and the Windows Boot Manager in Vista and later.
[src:windows-internals/windows-nt] The boot loader is responsible for accessing the file system on the boot drive, starting the kernel, and loading boot-time device drivers into memory.
[src:windows-internals/windows-nt] This process launches winlogon, which allows the user to log in.
[src:windows-internals/windows-nt] Once the user is logged in File Explorer is started, loading the graphical user interface of Windows NT.
[src:windows-internals/windows-nt] Windows NT is written in C and C++, with a very small amount written in assembly language.
[src:windows-internals/windows-nt] C is mostly used for the kernel code while C++ is mostly used for user-mode code.
[src:windows-internals/windows-nt] Assembly language is avoided where possible because it would impede portability and its usage is limited to just the most performance-critical portions (e.g. trap handlers, interrupt dispatch, system call stubs, context switching, HAL low‑level routines) of the codebase.
[src:windows-internals/windows-nt] The following are the releases of Windows based on the Windows NT technology.
[src:windows-internals/windows-nt] Windows NT 3.1 to 3.51 incorporated the Program Manager and File Manager from the Windows 3.1 series.
[src:windows-internals/windows-nt] Windows NT 4.0 onwards replaced those programs with Windows Explorer (including a taskbar and Start menu), which originally appeared in Windows 95.
[src:windows-internals/windows-nt] The first release was given version number 3.1 to match the contemporary 16-bit Windows; magazines of that era claimed the number was also used to make that version seem more reliable than a ".0" release.
[src:windows-internals/windows-nt] Also the Novell IPX protocol was apparently licensed only to 3.1 versions of Windows software.
[src:windows-internals/windows-nt] The NT version number is not now generally used for marketing purposes, but is still used internally, and said to reflect the degree of changes to the core of the operating system.
[src:windows-internals/windows-nt] However, for application compatibility reasons, Microsoft kept the major version number as 6 in releases following Vista, but changed it later to 10 in Windows 10.
[src:windows-internals/windows-nt] The build number is an internal identifier used by Microsoft's developers and beta testers.
[src:windows-internals/windows-nt] Starting with Windows 8.1, Microsoft changed the Version API Helper functions' behavior.
[src:windows-internals/windows-nt] If an application is not manifested for Windows 8.1 or later, the API will always return version 6.2, which is the version number of Windows 8.
[src:windows-internals/windows-nt] This is because the *manifest* feature was introduced with Windows 8.1, to replace GetVersion and related functions.
[src:windows-internals/windows-nt] In order to prevent Intel x86-specific code from slipping into the operating system, due to developers being used to developing on x86 chips, Windows NT 3.1 was initially developed using non-x86 development systems and then ported to the x86 architecture.
[src:windows-internals/windows-nt] This work was initially based on the Intel i860-based *Dazzle* system and, later, the MIPS R3000-based *Jazz* platform.
[src:windows-internals/windows-nt] Both systems were designed internally at Microsoft.
[src:windows-internals/windows-nt] Windows NT 3.1 was released for Intel x86 PC compatible and PC-98 platforms, and for DEC Alpha and ARC-compliant MIPS platforms.
[src:windows-internals/windows-nt] Only two of the Windows NT 4.0 variants (IA-32 and Alpha) have a full set of service packs available.
[src:windows-internals/windows-nt] All of the other ports done by third parties (Motorola, Intergraph, etc.) have few, if any, publicly available updates.
[src:windows-internals/windows-nt] On January 5, 2011, Microsoft announced that the next major version of the Windows NT family will include support for the ARM architecture.
[src:windows-internals/windows-nt] Microsoft demonstrated a preliminary version of Windows (version 6.2.7867) running on an ARM-based computer at the 2011 Consumer Electronics Show.
[src:windows-internals/windows-nt] This eventually led to the commercial release of the Windows 8-derived Windows RT on October 26, 2012, and the use of Windows NT, rather than Windows CE, in Windows Phone 8.
[src:windows-internals/windows-nt] The original Xbox and Xbox 360 run a custom operating system based upon a heavily modified version of Windows 2000, an approach that Microsoft engineer Don Box called "fork and run".
[src:windows-internals/windows-nt] It exports APIs similar to those found in Microsoft Windows, such as Direct3D.
[src:windows-internals/windows-nt] The Xbox One and Xbox Series X/S consoles use a stripped-down version of the Windows operating system.
[src:windows-internals/windows-nt] Windows 11 is the first non-server version of Windows NT that does not support 32-bit platforms.
[src:windows-internals/windows-nt] The 64-bit versions of Windows NT were originally intended to run on Itanium and DEC Alpha; the latter was used internally at Microsoft during early development of 64-bit Windows.
[src:windows-internals/windows-nt] This continued for some time after Microsoft publicly announced that it was cancelling plans to ship 64-bit Windows for Alpha.
[src:windows-internals/windows-nt] Because of this, Alpha versions of Windows NT are 32-bit only.
[src:windows-internals/windows-nt] While Windows 2000 only supports Intel IA-32 (32-bit), Windows XP, Server 2003, Server 2008 and Server 2008 R2 each have one edition dedicated to Itanium-based systems.
[src:windows-internals/windows-nt] In comparison with Itanium, Microsoft adopted x64 on a greater scale: every version of Windows since Windows XP (which has a dedicated x64 edition) has x64 editions.
[src:windows-internals/windows-nt] The first version of Windows NT to support ARM64 devices with Qualcomm processors was Windows 10, version 1709.
[src:windows-internals/windows-nt] This is a full version of Windows, rather than the cut-down Windows RT.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] The **Windows Registry** is a hierarchical database that stores low-level settings for the Microsoft Windows operating system and for applications that opt to use the registry.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] The kernel, device drivers, services, Security Accounts Manager, and user interfaces can all use the registry.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] The registry also allows access to counters for profiling system performance.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] In other words, the registry or Windows Registry contains information, settings, options, and other values for programs and hardware installed on all versions of Microsoft Windows operating systems.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] For example, when a program is installed, a new subkey containing settings such as a program's location, its version, and how to start the program, are all added to the Windows Registry.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] When introduced with Windows 3.1, the Windows Registry primarily stored configuration information for COM-based components.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] Windows 95 and Windows NT extended its use to rationalize and centralize the information in the profusion of INI files, which held the configurations for individual programs, and were stored at various locations.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] It is not a requirement for Windows applications to use the Windows Registry.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] For example, .NET Framework applications use XML files for configuration, while portable applications usually keep their configuration files with their executables.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] Prior to the Windows Registry, .INI files stored each program's settings as a text file or binary file, often located in a shared location that did not provide user-specific settings in a multi-user scenario.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] By contrast, the Windows Registry stores all application settings in one logical repository (but also in a number of discrete files) and in a standardized form.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] According to Microsoft, this offers several advantages over .INI files.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] Since file parsing is done much more efficiently with a binary format, it may be read from or written to more quickly than a text INI file.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] Furthermore, strongly typed data can be stored in the registry, as opposed to the text information stored in .INI files.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] This is a benefit when editing keys manually using regedit.exe, the built-in Windows Registry Editor.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] Because user-based registry settings are loaded from a user-specific path rather than from a read-only system location, the registry allows multiple users to share the same machine, and also allows programs to work for less privileged users.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] Backup and restoration is also simplified as the registry can be accessed over a network connection for remote management/support, including from scripts, using the standard set of APIs, as long as the Remote Registry service is running and firewall rules permit this.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] Because the registry is a database, it offers improved system integrity with features such as atomic updates.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] If two processes attempt to update the same registry value at the same time, one process's change will precede the other's and the overall consistency of the data will be maintained.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] Where changes are made to .INI files, such race conditions can result in inconsistent data that does not match either attempted update.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] Windows Vista and later operating systems provide transactional updates to the registry by means of the Kernel Transaction Manager, extending the atomicity guarantees across multiple key or value changes with traditional commit–abort semantics.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] The registry contains two basic elements: **keys** and **values**.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] Registry *keys* are container objects similar to folders.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] Registry *values* are non-container objects similar to files.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] Keys are referenced with a syntax similar to Windows' path names, using backslashes to indicate levels of hierarchy.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] Keys must have a case insensitive name without backslashes.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] For example, HKEY refers to the subkey "Windows" of the subkey "Microsoft" of the subkey "Software" of the HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE root key.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] Different users, programs, services or remote systems may only see some parts of the hierarchy or distinct hierarchies from the same root keys.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] Registry *values* are name/data pairs stored within keys.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] Registry values are referenced separately from registry keys.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] Each registry value stored in a registry key has a unique name whose letter case is not significant.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] The Windows API functions that query and manipulate registry values take value names separately from the key path or handle that identifies the parent key.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] Registry values may contain backslashes in their names, but doing so makes them difficult to distinguish from their key paths when using some legacy Windows Registry API functions (whose usage is deprecated in Win32).
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] The terminology is somewhat misleading, as each registry key is similar to an associative array, where standard terminology would refer to the name part of each registry value as a "key".
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] The terms are a holdout from the 16-bit registry in Windows 3, in which registry keys could not contain arbitrary name/data pairs, but rather contained only one unnamed value (which had to be a string).
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] In this sense, the Windows 3 registry was like a single associative array, in which the keys (in the sense of both 'registry key' and 'associative array key') formed a hierarchy, and the registry values were all strings.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] When the 32-bit registry was created, so was the additional capability of creating multiple named values per key, and the meanings of the names were somewhat distorted.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] For compatibility with the previous behavior, each registry key may have a "default" value, whose name is the empty string.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] Each value can store arbitrary data with variable length and encoding, but which is associated with a symbolic type (defined as a numeric constant) defining how to parse this data.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] The keys at the root level of the hierarchical database are generally named by their Windows API definitions, which all begin with HKEY They are frequently abbreviated to a three- or four-letter short name starting with "HK" (e.g.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] However, the converse may apply for administrator-enforced policy settings where HKLM may take precedence over HKCU.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] The Windows Logo Program has specific requirements for where different types of user data may be stored, and that the concept of least privilege be followed so that administrator-level access is not required to use an application.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] Abbreviated HKLM, HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE stores settings that are specific to the local computer.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] The key located by HKLM is actually not stored on disk, but maintained in memory by the system kernel in order to map all the other subkeys.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] Applications cannot create any additional subkeys.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] On Windows NT, this key contains four subkeys—SAM, SECURITY, SYSTEM, and SOFTWARE—that are loaded at boot time within their respective files located in the %SystemRoot%\System32\config\ folder.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] A fifth subkey, HARDWARE, is volatile and is created dynamically, and as such is not stored in a file (it exposes a view of all the currently detected Plug-and-Play devices).
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] On Windows Vista and above, a sixth and seventh subkey—COMPONENTS and BCD—are mapped in memory by the kernel on-demand and loaded from %SystemRoot%\System32\config\COMPONENTS or from boot configuration data, \boot\BCD on the system partition.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] Object Class IDs, tying them to the applications used to handle these items.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] keys for each user profile actively loaded on the machine, though user hives are usually only loaded for currently logged-in users.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] stores settings that are specific to the currently logged-in user.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] that corresponds to the user; the same information is accessible in both locations.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] inside their own Documents and Settings subfolder (or their own Users sub folder in Windows Vista and above).
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] provides runtime information into performance data provided by either the NT kernel itself, or running system drivers, programs and services that provide performance data.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] It contains information about hardware devices, including Plug and Play and network performance statistics.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] The information in this hive is also not stored on the hard drive; the Plug and Play information is gathered and configured at startup and is stored in memory.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] Even though the registry presents itself as an integrated hierarchical database, branches of the registry are actually stored in a number of disk files called *hives*.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] Some hives are volatile and are not stored on disk at all.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] An example of this is the hive of the branch starting at HKLM\HARDWARE.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] This hive records information about system hardware and is created each time the system boots and performs hardware detection.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] Individual settings for users on a system are stored in a hive (disk file) per user.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] During user login, the system loads the user hive under HKEY_USERS and sets the HKCU symbolic reference to point to the current user.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] This allows applications to store/retrieve settings for the current user implicitly under HKCU.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] Not all hives are loaded at any one time.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] At boot time, only a minimal set of hives are loaded, and after that, hives are loaded as the operating system initializes and as users log in or whenever a hive is explicitly loaded by an application.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] The registry is physically stored in several files, which are generally obfuscated from the user-mode APIs used to manipulate the data inside the registry.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] Depending upon the version of Windows, there will be different files and different locations for these files, but they are all on the local machine.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] The location for system registry files in Windows NT is %SystemRoot%\System32\config\; the user-specific HKEY_CURRENT_USER user registry hive is stored in Ntuser.dat inside the user profile.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] There is one of these per user; if a user has a roaming profile, then this file will be copied to and from a server at logout and login respectively.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] A second user-specific registry file named UsrClass.dat contains COM registry entries and does not roam by default.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] Windows NT systems store the registry in a binary file format which can be exported, loaded and unloaded by the Registry Editor in these operating systems.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] Windows 2000 keeps an alternate copy of the registry hives (.ALT) and attempts to switch to it when corruption is detected.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] Windows XP and Windows Server 2003 do not maintain a System.alt hive because NTLDR on those versions of Windows can process the System.log file to bring up to date a System hive that has become inconsistent during a shutdown or crash.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] In addition, the %SystemRoot%\Repair folder contains a copy of the system's registry hives that were created after installation and the first successful startup of Windows.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] Each registry data file has an associated file with a ".log" extension that acts as a transaction log that is used to ensure that any interrupted updates can be completed upon next startup.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] Internally, Registry files are split into 4 kB "bins" that contain collections of "cells".
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] The registry files are stored in %WINDIR% under the names USER.DAT and SYSTEM.DAT with the addition of CLASSES.DAT in Windows ME.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] Also, each user profile (if profiles are enabled) has its own USER.DAT file which is located in the user's profile directory in %WINDIR%\Profiles\<Username>\.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] The only registry file is called REG.DAT and it is stored in%WINDIR%.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] If any of the above methods worked, the device's registry files can be found in {Phone}\EFIESP\Windows\System32\config.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] The registry contains important configuration information for the operating system, for installed applications as well as individual settings for each user and application.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] A careless change to the operating system configuration in the registry could cause irreversible damage, so it is usually only installer programs which perform changes to the registry database during installation/configuration and removal.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] If a user wants to edit the registry manually, Microsoft recommends that a backup of the registry be performed before the change.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] When a program is removed from control panel, it may not be completely removed and, in case of errors or glitches caused by references to missing programs, the user might have to manually check inside directories such as program files.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] After this, the user might need to manually remove any reference to the uninstalled program in the registry.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] This is usually done by using RegEdit.exe.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] Editing the registry is sometimes necessary when working around Windows-specific issues e.g. problems when logging onto a domain can be resolved by editing the registry.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] Windows Registry can be edited manually using programs such as RegEdit.exe, although these tools do not expose some of the registry's metadata such as the last modified date.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] The registry editor for the 3.1/95 series of operating systems is RegEdit.exe and for Windows NT it is RegEdt32.exe; the functionalities are merged in Windows XP.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] Optional and third-party tools similar to RegEdit.exe are available for many Windows CE versions.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] .REG files (also known as Registration entries) are text-based human-readable files for exporting and importing portions of the registry using an INI-based syntax.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] Windows 9x format .REG files can be imported by Windows 2000 and later.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] These later systems also allow exporting .REG files in Windows 9x/NT format.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] String values do not require a <Value type> (see example), but backslashes (\) need to be written as a double-backslash (\\), and quotes (") as backslash-quote (\").
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] Data from .REG files can be added/merged with the registry by double-clicking these files or using the /s switch in the command line.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] REG files can also be used to remove registry data.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] To remove a key (and all subkeys, values and data), the key name must be preceded by a minus sign (-).
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] To remove a value (and its data), the values to be removed must have a minus sign (-) after the equal sign ({{{1}}}).
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] Windows group policies can change registry keys for a number of machines or individual users based on policies.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] When a policy first takes effect for a machine or for an individual user of a machine, the registry settings specified as part of the policy are applied to the machine or user settings.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] Windows will also look for updated policies and apply them periodically, typically every 90 minutes.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] Through its *scope* a policy defines to which machines and users the policy is to be applied.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] Whether a machine or user is within the scope of a policy or not is defined by a set of rules which can filter on the location of the machine or user account in organizational directory, specific users or machine accounts or security groups.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] More advanced rules can be set up using Windows Management Instrumentation expressions.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] Such rules can filter on properties such as computer vendor name, CPU architecture, installed software, or networks connected to.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] For instance, the administrator can create a policy with one set of registry settings for machines in the accounting department and policy with another (lock-down) set of registry settings for kiosk terminals in the visitors area.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] When a machine is moved from one scope to another (e.g., changing its name or moving it to another organizational unit), the correct policy is automatically applied.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] When a policy is changed it is automatically re-applied to all machines currently in its scope.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] The policy is edited through a number of administrative templates which provides a user interface for picking and changing settings.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] The set of administrative templates is extensible and software packages which support such remote administration can register their own templates.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] The registry can be manipulated in a number of ways from the command line.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] The Reg.exe and RegIni.exe utility tools are included in Windows XP and later versions of Windows.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] Alternative locations for legacy versions of Windows include the Resource Kit CDs or the original Installation CD of Windows.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] The /s means the file will be *silent merged* to the registry.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] If the /s parameter is omitted the user will be asked to confirm the operation.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] In Windows 98, Windows 95 and at least some configurations of Windows XP the /s switch also causes RegEdit.exe to ignore the setting in the registry that allows administrators to disable it.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] When using the /s switch RegEdit.exe does not return an appropriate return code if the operation fails, unlike Reg.exe which does.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] export the specified (sub)key (which has to be enclosed in quotes if it contains spaces) only.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] exports the whole registry in V4 format to an ANSI .REG file.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] exports the specified (sub)key (which has to be enclosed in quotes if it contains spaces) only.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] Other command line options include a VBScript or JScript together with CScript, WMI or WMIC.exe and Windows PowerShell.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] Registry permissions can be manipulated through the command line using RegIni.exe and the {{{1}}} tool.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] Windows PowerShell comes with a registry provider which presents the registry as a location type similar to the file system.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] The same commands used to manipulate files and directories in the file system can be used to manipulate keys and values of the registry.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] Also like the file system, PowerShell uses the concept of a *current location* which defines the context on which commands by default operate.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] The Get-ChildItem (also available through the aliases ls, dir or gci) retrieves the child keys of the current location.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] By using the Set-Location (or the alias cd) command the user can change the current location to another key of the registry.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] Commands which rename items, remove items, create new items or set content of items or properties can be used to rename keys, remove keys or entire sub-trees or change values.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] Through PowerShell scripts files, an administrator can prepare scripts which, when executed, make changes to the registry.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] Such scripts can be distributed to administrators who can execute them on individual machines.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] The PowerShell Registry provider supports transactions, i.e. multiple changes to the registry can be bundled into a single atomic transaction.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] An atomic transaction ensures that either all of the changes are committed to the database, or if the script fails, none of the changes are committed to the database.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] The registry can be edited through the APIs of the Advanced Windows 32 Base API Library (advapi32.dll).
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] Many programming languages offer built-in runtime library functions or classes that wrap the underlying Windows APIs and thereby enable programs to store settings in the registry (e.g.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] Microsoft.Win32.Registry in VB.NET and C#, or TRegistry in Delphi and Free Pascal).
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] COM-enabled applications like Visual Basic 6 can use the WSH WScript.Shell object.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] Another way is to use the Windows Resource Kit Tool, Reg.exe by executing it from code, although this is considered poor programming practice.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] Similarly, scripting languages such as Perl (with Win32::TieRegistry), Python (with winreg), Tcl (which comes bundled with the registry package), Windows Powershell and Windows Scripting Host also enable registry editing from scripts.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] The offreg.dll file, available from the Windows Driver Kit, offers a set of APIs for the creation and manipulation of currently not loaded registry hives similar to those provided by advapi32.dll.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] It is also possible to edit the registry (hives) of an offline system from Windows PE or Linux (in the latter case using open source tools).
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] Prior to the introduction of registration-free COM, developers were encouraged to add initialization code to in-process and out-of-process binaries to perform the registry configuration required for that object to work.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] COM applications that break because of DLL Hell issues can commonly be repaired with RegSvr32.exe or the /RegServer switch without having to re-invoke installation programs.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] Windows exposes APIs that allows user-mode applications to register to receive a notification event if a particular registry key is changed.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] APIs are also available to allow kernel-mode applications to filter and modify registry calls made by other applications.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] Windows also supports remote access to the registry of another computer via the RegConnectRegistry function if the Remote Registry service is running, correctly configured and its network traffic is not firewalled.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] Each key in the registry of Windows NT versions can have an associated security descriptor.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] The security descriptor contains an access control list (ACL) that describes which user groups or individual users are granted or denied access permissions.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] The set of registry permissions include 10 rights/permissions which can be explicitly allowed or denied to a user or a group of users.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] As with other securable objects in the operating system, individual access control entries (ACE) on the security descriptor can be explicit or inherited from a parent object.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] Windows Resource Protection is a feature of Windows Vista and later versions of Windows that uses security to deny Administrators and the system WRITE access to some sensitive keys to protect the integrity of the system from malware and accidental modification.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] Special ACEs on the security descriptor can also implement mandatory integrity control for the registry key and subkeys.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] A process running at a lower integrity level cannot write, change or delete a registry key/value, even if the account of the process has otherwise been granted access through the ACL.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] For instance, Internet Explorer running in Protected Mode can *read* medium and low integrity registry keys/values of the currently logged on user, but it can only modify low integrity keys.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] Outside security, registry keys cannot be deleted or edited due to other causes.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] Registry keys containing NUL characters cannot be deleted with standard registry editors and require a special utility for deletion, such as RegDelNull.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] Windows 2000 and later versions of Windows use Group Policy to enforce registry settings through a registry-specific client extension in the Group Policy processing engine.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] Policy may be applied locally to a single computer using gpedit.msc or to multiple users and computers in a domain using gpmc.msc.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] With Windows 95, Windows 98, Windows ME and Windows NT 4.0, administrators can use a special file to be merged into the registry, called a policy file (POLICY.POL).
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] The policy file allows administrators to prevent non-administrator users from changing registry settings like, for instance, the security level of Internet Explorer and the desktop background wallpaper.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] The policy file is primarily used in a business with a large number of computers where the business needs to be protected from rogue or careless users.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] The default extension for the policy file is .POL.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] The policy file filters the settings it enforces by user and by group (a "group" is a defined set of users).
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] To do that the policy file merges into the registry, preventing users from circumventing it by simply changing back the settings.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] The policy file is usually distributed through a LAN, but can be placed on the local computer.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] The policy file is created by a free tool by Microsoft that goes by the filename poledit.exe for Windows 95/Windows 98 and with a computer management module for Windows NT.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] The editor requires administrative permissions to be run on systems that uses permissions.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] The editor can also directly change the current registry settings of the local computer and if the remote registry service is installed and started on another computer it can also change the registry on that computer.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] The policy editor loads the settings it can change from .ADM files, of which one is included, that contains the settings the Windows shell provides.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] The .ADM file is plain text and supports easy localization by allowing all the strings to be stored in one place.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] Windows NT kernels support redirection of INI file-related APIs into a virtual file in a registry location such as HKEY_CURRENT_USER using a feature called "InifileMapping".
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] This functionality was introduced to allow legacy applications written for 16-bit versions of Windows to be able to run under Windows NT platforms on which the System folder is no longer considered an appropriate location for user-specific data or configuration.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] Non-compliant 32-bit applications can also be redirected in this manner, even though the feature was originally intended for 16-bit applications.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] Similarly, application virtualization redirects all of an application's invalid registry operations to a location such as a file.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] Used together with file virtualization, this allows applications to run on a machine without being installed on it.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] Low integrity processes may also use registry virtualization.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] For example, Internet Explorer 7 or 8 running in "Protected Mode" on Windows Vista and above will automatically redirect registry writes by ActiveX controls to a sandboxed location in order to frustrate some classes of security exploits.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] The Application Compatibility Toolkit provides shims that can transparently redirect HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE or HKEY_CLASSES_ROOT Registry operations to HKEY_CURRENT_USER to address "LUA" bugs that cause applications not to work for users with insufficient rights.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] Critics labeled the registry in Windows 95 a single point of failure, because re-installation of the operating system was required if the registry became corrupt.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] However, Windows NT uses transaction logs to protect against corruption during updates.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] Current versions of Windows use two levels of log files to ensure integrity even in the case of power failure or similar catastrophic events during database updates.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p01] Even in the case of a non-recoverable error, Windows can repair or re-initialize damaged registry entries during system boot.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p02] In Windows, use of the registry for storing program data is a matter of developer's discretion.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p02] Microsoft provides programming interfaces for storing data in XML files (via MSXML) or database files (via SQL Server Compact) which developers can use instead.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p02] Developers are also free to use non-Microsoft alternatives or develop their own proprietary data stores.
[src:windows-internals/windows-registry-p02] In contrast to Windows Registry's binary-based database model, some other operating systems use separate plain-text files for daemon and application configuration, but group these configurations together for ease of management.
